Task: Dynamically change log level with tracing rust

 <p>I am using the tracer library and have setup a console and file logger which is working.</p>
<pre><code>let file = OpenOptions::new()
  .append(true)
  .create(true)
  .open(&quot;logfile.log&quot;)
  .unwrap();

let subscriber = Registry::default()
  .with(
    // stdout layer
    fmt::layer()
      .compact()
      .with_ansi(true)
      .with_filter(filter::LevelFilter::from_level(Level::INFO)),
  )
  .with(
    // File layer
    fmt::layer()
      .with_ansi(false)
      .with_writer(file)
      .with_filter(filter::LevelFilter::from_level(Level::INFO)),
  );

tracing::subscriber::set_global_default(subscriber).unwrap();
</code></pre>
<p>I want to be able to dynamically change the log level.
I have tried looking at: <a href="https://docs.rs/tracing-subscriber/latest/tracing_subscriber/reload/index.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://docs.rs/tracing-subscriber/latest/tracing_subscriber/reload/index.html</a>
and
<a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/72159366/how-can-i-change-the-log-level-on-the-fly-with-tracing">How can I change the log level on the fly with tracing?</a> and also some examples in src/reload.rs in the library.</p>
<pre><code>let filtered_layer = fmt::Layer::default().with_filter(filter::LevelFilter::INFO);
let (filtered_layer, reload_handle) = reload::Layer::new(filtered_layer);
tracing_subscriber::registry()
  .with(filtered_layer)
  .init(); // Panic here
reload_handle.modify(|layer| *layer.filter_mut() = filter::LevelFilter::ERROR);

let filtered_layer = fmt::Layer::default().with_filter(filter::LevelFilter::ERROR);
let (filtered_layer, reload_handle) = reload::Layer::new(filtered_layer);
</code></pre>
<p>If I under stand correctly this should fetch all layers which have a LevelFilter::INFO filter, then these can be modified? I get a panic on the 3rd line that the default can only be set once per program lifetime. Is it possible to change the level of only 1 of the layers, like only the console. When omitting the 3rd line the code executes but the level has not changed.</p>


