Task: Flipping line of 4-Byte pixels horizontally

 <p>I must flip some lines of pixels around their centers (<strong>not</strong> the whole image).
My first solution in simple, safe Rust was this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>/** It's a square, each side (width &amp; height) is PIXELS_PER_SIDE long.
And flip &gt;&gt;some&lt;&lt; lines, &gt;&gt;not&lt;&lt; flip everything! */
const PIXELS_PER_SIDE: usize = 8;
const PIXELS_PER_LINE: usize = PIXELS_PER_SIDE;
const BYTES_PER_PIXEL: usize = 4;

/// Flip a single line, [`flip_lines()`] is a different function.
fn flip_line(line_bytes: &amp;mut [u8]) {
    for i in 0..PIXELS_PER_LINE / 2 {
        let left_index = i * BYTES_PER_PIXEL;
        let right_index = (PIXELS_PER_LINE - 1 - i) * BYTES_PER_PIXEL;

        line_bytes.swap(left_index, right_index);
        line_bytes.swap(left_index + 1, right_index + 1);
        line_bytes.swap(left_index + 2, right_index + 2);
        line_bytes.swap(left_index + 3, right_index + 3);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Since this should run on weak embedded Hardware with 60 fps, like old Raspberry Pi's, which have still enough power for the Standard library, and I couldn't find something fundamentally better, I asked GPT 5.1-Codex for a faster solution. It came up with this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn flip_line(line_bytes: &amp;mut [u8]) {
    debug_assert_eq!(line_bytes.len() % BYTES_PER_PIXEL, 0);
    let mut left = 0;
    let mut right = line_bytes.len().saturating_sub(BYTES_PER_PIXEL);

    while left &lt; right {
        unsafe {
            std::ptr::swap_nonoverlapping(
                line_bytes.as_mut_ptr().add(left),
                line_bytes.as_mut_ptr().add(right),
                BYTES_PER_PIXEL,
            );
        }
        left += BYTES_PER_PIXEL;
        right = right.saturating_sub(BYTES_PER_PIXEL);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Examining GPTs suggestion I see that it seems more efficient, especially since it's mostly <code>#[inline]</code> code, I'm still not convinced.
I was hoping more for some intrinsic calls, which work on AMD64 and ARM64. Given that these are <em>very</em> basic byte operations with promising numbers: 4 Bytes per pixel and 8 times that.</p>
<p>Can this be made more efficient?</p>
<p><strong>Edit: Because an <em>almost</em> working solution was posted, I add the test-code for this</strong><br>
Using the <code>asserting</code> crate:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use ...flip_line;
    use asserting::assertions::AssertEquality;
    use asserting::spec::assert_that;

    const ORIGINAL_BYTES: [u8; BYTES_PER_PIXEL * PIXELS_PER_LINE] = [
        // 0
        1, 2, 3, 4, //
        // 1
        5, 6, 7, 8, //
        // 2
        9, 10, 11, 12, //
        // 3
        13, 14, 15, 16, //
        // --------------------
        // 4
        17, 18, 19, 20, //
        // 5
        21, 22, 23, 24, //
        // 6
        25, 26, 27, 28, //
        // 7
        29, 30, 31, 32,
    ];

    const TARGETED_BYTES: [u8; BYTES_PER_PIXEL * PIXELS_PER_LINE] = [
        // 7
        29, 30, 31, 32, //
        // 6
        25, 26, 27, 28, //
        // 5
        21, 22, 23, 24, //
        // 4
        17, 18, 19, 20, //
        // --------------------
        // 3
        13, 14, 15, 16, //
        // 2
        9, 10, 11, 12, //
        // 1
        5, 6, 7, 8, //
        // 0
        1, 2, 3, 4, //
    ];

    #[test]
    fn test_flip_line() {
        let mut mutated_bytes: [u8; 32] = ORIGINAL_BYTES;
        flip_line(&amp;mut mutated_bytes);

        assert_that(mutated_bytes).is_equal_to(TARGETED_BYTES);
    }
}
</code></pre>


